The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 IFC to pick up stake in Lanco firm

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Mumbai, June 7: International Finance Corporation (IFC), the private sector arm of the World Bank group, will pick up a 5.84 per cent stake, amounting to $8 million, in Lanco Amarkantak Power. 

 Lanco Amarkantak is developing a thermal power station in Chhattisgarh comprising two coal-based units of 300mw each. It is a special purpose vehicle promoted by the Lanco group, which operates in power generation and trading, realty, engineering and construction, information technology and manufacturing. 

 At present, the power portfolio of the group includes an operating capacity of 518mw. Additional capacities under construction aggregate to more than 3,200mw. 

 The construction and engineering division of the company is executing orders worth more than Rs 5,000 crore.

 The project at Chhattisgarh is estimated to cost around Rs 2,600 crore and is scheduled for completion in 2008. According to Lanco, DEG, the private sector arm of KFW banking group of Germany, has committed to pick up a 9 per cent stake in Lanco Amarkantak. Lanco Infratech Ltd owns 75.16 per cent.

 Recently, Lancos ABAN Power Company, a natural gas-based power project, was registered as a clean development mechanism (CDM) project with the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change. ABAN is the first natural gas-based unit worldwide to be registered as a CDM project. 




